equation_narrative.headline: Polar context from local sequence drives Q selection over E competitor
equation_narrative.story: Position 62 in ubiquitin sits in a polar-rich local environment (SDYNI[Q]KESTL) with three structural contacts. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation that shifts from hydrophobic-leaning (alanine peaks at 23% at L12) to increasingly polar as local sequence features dominate. The representation character remains ambiguous through L23, with no clear polar/charged preference. At L27-31, the decision phase activates: Q-specific prediction channels emerge, and MLP neurons cast decisive votes distinguishing Q from its close competitor E. Q surges from 2% at L23 to 75% by L33, overtaking E at L31.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather context from three structural contacts and strong local sequence signal. Early layers (L1-9) show high-projection attention features (F1:9146, F9:5728 both >45 proj) encoding position identity and local chemistry. The logit lens initially projects toward hydrophobic residues—alanine peaks at 23% at L12, reflecting the model's encoding of buried context from structural neighbors. Through L8-17, the representation shifts as local sequence features accumulate: serine and leucine alternate in the logit lens (lead changes at L8, L9, L11, L12, L14), indicating the model is encoding the polar-hydrophobic mixed character of the surrounding sequence. By L18-23, glycine briefly peaks (11% at L21), suggesting the model has encoded flexibility or turn-prone character. No co-evolutionary signal arrives (0 coevolving positions), so the representation is built entirely from local and structural context.
perception_phase.context_character: The biochemical context by L23 is polar-rich local sequence (SDYNI_KESTL with multiple charged and polar neighbors) with three structural contacts. The representation remains chemically ambiguous—the logit lens shows no dominant character, with small probabilities distributed across hydrophobic (A, L), polar (S, G), and charged (Q, E) residues.

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L27-31. At L27, Q-specific MLP neurons activate (N27:3518 votes +0.48 for Q, N27:750 +0.41, N27:4524 +0.39), pushing Q from 2% to 10%. At L28, attention delivers a massive +6.79 delta toward Q. At L31, the final commitment occurs: N31:3170 writes +1.01 for Q, N31:1142 +0.66, and Q surges from 17% to 38%, overtaking E. By L33, Q reaches 75% as late-stage prediction channels (F33:9048 with 93.2 proj) lock in the answer.
decision_phase.transition: The L23-25 boundary marks the shift from perception to decision. At L23, the representation is still ambiguous (Q at 2.4%, L leading at 20.6%). At L24, AA-specific prediction features first appear with moderate projections (F24:7887, F24:10103 ~9 proj), but the representation remains uncertain. By L27, high-specificity MLP neurons activate, casting real votes for Q versus E, and the model commits to a polar residue.

At L28, attention delivers +6.79 delta (largest velocity event), and Q reaches 19%. At L31, the final surge occurs: N31:3170 writes +1.01, N31:2708 +0.80, N31:1142 +0.66, and Q jumps from 17% to 38%, overtaking E. By L33, Q dominates at 75% as final prediction channels (F33:9048 with 93.2 proj, F33:6423 with 87.1 proj) lock in the answer.

candidates.narrative: E is Q's closest competitor, peaking at 39% at L28 before losing to Q. E benefits from similar polar context as Q—both are polar/charged residues fitting the local environment. At L27-29, E-supporting neurons activate (N28:3703 +0.38 for E, N22:4622 +0.33), and E briefly leads at L27 (23% vs Q's 19%). However, at L31, Q-specific neurons dominate, and E falls to 17%, then 14% by L33. The model distinguishes Q from E based on subtle differences in side-chain chemistry encoded in late-stage MLP neurons.

candidates.narrative: Alanine dominates the logit lens through L1-23, peaking at 23% at L12. This does NOT mean the model predicts alanine—rather, the representation at these layers is hydrophobic-leaning, consistent with the model encoding buried structural contacts and hydrophobic neighbors in the local sequence. As local polar features accumulate (L15-23), alanine declines steadily (23% → 7%), and by the decision phase (L24+), alanine is irrelevant (1% at L33). The early alanine signal reflects the representation's character during context assembly, not a prediction.

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic-leaning to chemically ambiguous. At L12, alanine peaks at 23%, reflecting the model's encoding of buried structural contacts. Through L12-17, MLP neurons erase hydrophobic signal (N13:4397 -0.20, N14:319 -0.31, N15:1790 -0.17) while polar-encoding neurons activate (N15:4553 +0.37 for E/Q, N15:424 +0.29 for D/E/Q). The logit lens shifts from alanine-dominant to a mixed distribution (S, L, A all ~15-20% at L17), indicating the model has integrated polar features from the local sequence.

The decision phase begins. At L27, Q-specific MLP neurons activate (N27:3518 +0.48, N27:750 +0.41, N27:4524 +0.39), pushing Q from 2% to 10%. At L28, attention delivers the largest velocity event (+6.79 delta toward Q), and Q surges to 19%. E briefly peaks at 39% at L28, but Q is rising faster. This is the transition from ambiguous representation to committed prediction—the model has assembled sufficient polar context to distinguish Q from E.

The final commitment. At L31, Q-specific neurons dominate: N31:3170 writes +1.01, N31:2708 +0.80, N31:1142 +0.66. Q surges from 17% to 38%, overtaking E (which falls to 17%). At L32-33, final prediction channels activate (N32:4119 +1.09, F33:9048 93.2 proj, F33:6423 87.1 proj), and Q reaches 75%. E is suppressed by erasers (N31:1177 -1.05, N32:1747 -1.25), falling to 14%. The model has committed: Q is the answer.

deep_dives.label: Early attention features (L1-9)
deep_dives.caption: These high-projection features (>45 proj) encode position identity and local chemistry during initial context assembly. F1:9146, F1:5480, F9:5728 are among the strongest, establishing the baseline representation before structural and polar features accumulate.

deep_dives.label: Hydrophobic erasure (L12-17)
deep_dives.caption: Watch how MLP neurons erase the early hydrophobic signal. N13:4397 (-0.20), N14:319 (-0.31), N15:1790 (-0.17) suppress alanine/leucine as polar-encoding neurons (N15:4553 +0.37, N15:424 +0.29) activate. This is the representation shifting from hydrophobic-leaning to polar-compatible.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention (L31-32)
deep_dives.caption: L31 H1 erases with -4.18 proj and 0.789 structural attention, reading the three structural contacts. L32 H14 writes +2.57 with 0.456 structural attention. These heads integrate 3D context into the final decision, though local sequence dominates.

deep_dives.label: Decision onset MLP (L27-28)
deep_dives.caption: The decision phase begins here. At L27, Q-specific neurons activate (N27:3518 +0.48, N27:750 +0.41, N27:4524 +0.39). At L28, the MLP is net negative (-4.30 total), but Q-supporting neurons (N28:2326 +0.42, N28:563 +0.40, N28:3703 +0.38) push Q forward while erasers suppress competitors.

deep_dives.label: Final commitment MLP (L31-32)
deep_dives.caption: The decisive layers. N31:3170 (+1.01), N31:2708 (+0.80), N31:1142 (+0.66) cast the strongest votes for Q. N32:4119 (+1.09) locks in the answer. Erasers (N31:1177 -1.05, N32:1747 -1.25) suppress E and other competitors. Total MLP projection: +4.10 at L31, +5.71 at L32.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction channels (L33)
deep_dives.caption: The highest-projection features at L33 are Q-specific prediction channels. F33:9048 (93.2 proj), F33:6423 (87.1 proj), F33:303 (85.1 proj) encode the final answer. These are the model's output representation for Q at this position.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts Q by assembling a polar-rich local context (SDYNI_KESTL with charged neighbors K and E) and distinguishing Q from its close competitor E through late-stage MLP neurons. The strongest evidence is the L31 surge: N31:3170 (+1.01), N31:2708 (+0.80), and N31:1142 (+0.66) cast decisive votes for Q, pushing it from 17% to 38% and overtaking E. The decision hinges on subtle side-chain chemistry encoded in these neurons, which favor Q's amide group over E's carboxylate. With only three structural contacts and no co-evolutionary signal, the model relies almost entirely on local sequence—and gets it right.
